The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
EZ stock transactions reached about half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of trading Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday’s drop when it dropped to about 6%.
The drop this time is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
Also expressed here is the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the stabilization plan of the secretary of the financial sector.
Falling Stocks in Asia
Asian stocks fell dramatically on Tuesday, though the index eventually eased some of the losses over the course of the day.
Hong Kong's Hang Seng stock index throughout its trading day hit nearly four percent, though it later eased its losses by reducing the decline by nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movements of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
Shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the Index Secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The rescue actions planned in the US are unsafe and this influences the financial market around the world,” said the head of the Hong Kong Currency Office, Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it only determines its monetary policy, that is, without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should reconvene as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the falls will be felt in other countries.
Bloody Bath of American Stocks
On Monday, the American Assembly of Representatives rejected the aid plan for the financial system, which should be allocated 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion crowns).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks took a bloody dip and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell to almost seven percent, a similar drop in volume was last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before it was announced, but as soon as it was shown that the proposal of the assembly was not moving forward, the index began to fall freely.
Congress pulls out: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banking
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed to a pact on broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
Its vote will take place early next week.
American lawmakers caused a gap in talks over the approval of the rescue plan in its form of aid to the American financial system with the amount of 700 billion dollars (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and have it voted on.
The financial aid plan will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could take place in the Senate no earlier than Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the rescue plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
Then, however, there will be "disenchantment" thanks to the complex mechanisms whose help to the market will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a great advance.
We settled our differing opinions on how the market stabilization package should be shaped,” Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still take place on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met Sunday night with Finance Minister Henry Paulson to finalize the government fund.
It should buy from financial corporations the unsold mortgage assets that drive financial firms to severe losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we’re already in it,” Paulson said.
A sign for Asian businesses
The global financial crisis has a clear impact on the fast-moving stock market.
According to Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., lawmakers are doing everything they can to get Congress to definitively pass a deal on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors’ business before the Asian finance market as these are the ones that are in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for now there is nothing clear for sure about when the two chambers of Congress will vote and, even, if they will not stagnate at the last moment with some problem.
Lawmakers believe it will pass in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion needs to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it has the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, which would be another 100 billion dollars and, later, the last 350 billion dollars.
Bush praised the progress of the meetings.
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision but Congress can overcome its veto by a majority of votes.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was to earn financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage securities whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to finish paying their mortgages.
“We’ve worked everything out.
The Assembly of Representatives should be prepared to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is pleased with Saturday's move and that he appreciates "the commitment of both sides to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy."
Limitation of the armoured contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said lawmakers decided on responsibility for the program’s money to protect taxpayers’ taxes from their losses, an alleviating shutdown of the scheduled financial plan.
The new law must also limit the so-called armored contracts for directors of the companies participating in the program, and creates a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This should be directed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've worked very hard on it, and we've made a big step toward a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also counts on helping homeowners who struggle with their payments.
The government would have to agree on the new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower the monthly burden on borrowers’ installment payments and enable them to keep their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but quite difficult.
“And this is why it is not known with what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought.
This will be decisive for the division of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week, for the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not, according to Marek, as relevant.
“Much more important is that, already this week, the congressmen agree on their support and give their approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to get that approval is, at the moment, the most important thing," Marek insisted.
Armed struggle: the MP3 Player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player gets to make calls.
It seems that it is better to buy only the phone.
There are still enough reasons for the man to acquire only the player.
The choice depends practically on the manner of its use and the demand of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for you to acquire the most modern record player to listen on it the latest album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the other hand, this type of musical products such as LP records no longer come out, and as far as their quality is concerned, there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music crowd your shelves, you are probably dreaming, at least, of this type of record player.
This is the same with music that is on the way, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as well as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try twenty-crown market helmets.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life.
Some of the best players achieve much more than just playing music and even what not even most mobiles.
No device today is as universal as the telephone.
Faced with the most elementary functions such as calling, sending messages, can play music and video, record both, has a better or worse photography device and can even navigate.
And when we take into consideration the Smartphone and the PDAs they will also have in their pocket a small computer.
This is a small miracle since no fridge knows how to make a barbecue and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobiles also brings us disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the sooner the display prompt will light up asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy swallows.
Few are the mobiles that manage to play music more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) clearly have a higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobile phones will not play more than two hours.
If in addition to this, above, constantly call still get yourself, for more safety, a charger for work - this applies also to the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have it, because even the worst endure at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a load.
Another problem occurs when recording music on mobile.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only in some unreduced reader units can the small memory cards used in mobile phones be connected.
On players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is needed.
Simply fill the device with music through the USB of the computer.
Most mobiles and players create their order in the music library alone according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to the user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a particular equipment, be interested in the resistance of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to the music as a background and you will listen to it every day only for a while, as in the tram, then it is enough with any mobile that plays.
What virtually any mobile truly achieves.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or the player play the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and practically all the music that comes to it will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for him the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The least include the AAC format (format used by the company Apple and your iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or album.
This service could be on its own a compelling argument to acquire a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is miserable and most are limited only to the issues of fleeting success of radios.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a mobile phone.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you will find the mobile in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, handsfree.
If not, you can use a built-in player that has virtually every phone even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobile with music will be its price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns can already acquire a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone jack.
The best, even in terms of the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input for a classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous common cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic account for data download.
Which device to decide on
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example, the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card you will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are usually equipped with only a card of 2 GB maximum capacity.
Only the most expensive ones have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you consider yourself among the most demanding music lovers, take advantage of the most specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose phones of the walkman line have almost identical use as that of a separate MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, about four thousand crowns, but with a greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (normally 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned above brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we are still missing something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long in coming.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (CTO) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming rates will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that in the Czech market there is extreme competition.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (CTO), Pavel Dvosák, has already stated that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant price decrease, which had to be reacted to by classic operators.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
No need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Just after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often counteracted with the offer of tighter services.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically aimed at man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and who can be trusted,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav ?epick? said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated.”
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," Jana Studniková, a spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, said in a phone conversation to mobil.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a mobile virtual operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in it, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times are flashing.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly as early as the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sr?e?, spokesperson for Telefónica O2.
Other operators are concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2’s opinion, adds: “To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to be developed.”
“On the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find a virtual carrier until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some specific contract that was possible to study in such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav ?epick? adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with toenail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a decrease in prices and with it, a decrease in profits.
So why facilitate entry to the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of that is the grab when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on the company was at the time of the entry of U:fon by T-Mobile.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the websites of the “T”.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the EU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (OHS).
However, she expressed her typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement was concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
Until today no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential interested parties was not interesting enough for the classic operators," added Kristián Chalupa, from the foreign relations department of the OHS.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, apart from this they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of the OHS.
Really how dramatically shocking in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility for their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecom regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Obviously there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by the T according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial bidding a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another insight - for a virtual operator to emerge the agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - in all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for OHS should represent a warning the fact that three mobile operators ascend strikingly in a similar way.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all the negotiations with the operators they encounter many similar impediments.
Charging the responsibility in the t-shirt is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the t-shirt washes its hands in all this matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently introduced to extend the competence of the Commission in the field of commercial tenders which was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known by the representatives of ?OHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
All is well, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator continues to work unnoticed, as there are quite a few in Czech mobile phone networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as the ones you cite were discovered, you could talk about breach of contract conditions that could result in the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová answered the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that an activity of this kind carried out by mobile phone operators did not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they obtain not negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name so they can not absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators.
Precisely this is what it should seem to the minimally strange T.
There is also a new question for the OHS.
If mobile operators are blindsided by this type of procedure, why are they blocking the virtual operator’s entry?
It is necessary to add that the OHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, classic operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this incursion.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have intervened at the moment and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Either with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to get the first virtual operator to emerge and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body passes this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really comes to these lands, then the Czech mobile market will probably start moving again.
If one of the operators lets in a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
