The Prague MHD takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, the tram and the bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company.
It can be purchased right now by almost a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from January 1, 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the infocenters and stations of the transport company at the Metro stations, Muzeum, M?stek, Nádra?í Hole?ovice, And?l, Roztyly, Let?any, Kobylisy, Rajská?
The bonds can already be purchased on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticket stands at metro stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard is reloaded at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is available to passengers a window with prepared personnel that helps the interested parties with the purchase online and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card," said the spokesman of the project, Martin Opatrn.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to top up the electronic voucher on the Opencard in the automatic vending machines found in some metro lobbies.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket-picking machine and travelers will probably have already noticed them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budajovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
“There are now five in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty,” Opatrin said.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start operating tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
Electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the ring trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 used mainly by the inhabitants of the localities of central Bohemia.
"On the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the voucher," explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization that establishes the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
The ring buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver's locker.
Upon entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also it is necessary to accompany it with the Opencard in the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the voucher.
“If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the vouchers there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,” Drápal said.
Passengers who do not travel on the ring buses and do not remember when the validity of the voucher ends can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
