In a city apart, the pride and trials of color life
Hidden away by the park’s sprawling theme of big Orlando, a few miles from the bright, noisy, colossal city, lies a quiet town, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are all too evident.
Eatonville, the first completely black-inhabited city incorporated into the country and childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: “the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 colored men, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and not a jail.”
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described – making it also a tourist stage by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression Season Federal Writers Project – remains a separate place.
The city remains independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Ms. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resist sharing their true ideas with the white man, who “knows so little about us and doesn’t know what he’s missing.”
Even now, in the year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has drawn attention to start a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain cautious in the face of the outsider.
“We’re very cautious about the way our story is told,” said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historic model of Black affirmation and a community of nearly 2,400 people living under a poverty level twice the national average.
It is a literary center, but also a repaired example of the rural culture of the Black South - sometimes scorned, sometimes praised - that was born out of slavery in America.
No wonder, if those who reside here are both proud and reserved.
And the preoccupation with Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her profound books in dialect such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in Florida’s guidebook transformed the city, just off Route 17, a highway that runs through central Florida often forgotten in the history of blacks and human drama.
Bearing a cement face both in life and in literature, Ms. Hurston took her readers to the shop owned by Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
“Off the road on the left,” he wrote, “there is the modern Maron public school with its white finishes, its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds, tended by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write.”
She also mentions widow Dash's new husband and writes that Glenn Lee "sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transient rooms."
Thus, in just a few hundred words, Mrs. Hurston puts Eatonville in relation to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Obviously, this Fodor did not.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
“Zora described it as it was,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls Ms. Hurston immortalized by quoting men singing colorless songs about her beauty.
He added: “Some people didn’t like that.”
Ms. Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77, remembers that when Mrs. Hurston arrived in town, she did so without warning in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on dressing with dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcastically.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin continues.
But, she adds, swaying in her chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Mrs. Hurston was probably baptized, “she never stayed too long.”
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no large memorial ceremonies, no large public readings.
"I don't think her contribution to the world or her heritage was understood," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Mrs. Hurston published in 2003.
A certain turn came in the '80s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane road through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the labor community’s main two-lane street.
The expansion of the Orlando area had already pushed Interstate 4 across the city’s western edge.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended him relatively idyllic isolation from the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle for racial mixing brought hatred about the community.
“During that season, a group of white boys would go around the city throwing oranges and everything at the people sitting next to them,” Mr. Franklin said.
"They killed a girl once, too.
They threw him against a car watermelon."
In a 1955 letter to Mrs. Hurston, she wrote to The Orlando Sentinel, criticizing the forced integration by the Supreme Court that, in Brown v. Board of Education, "insulted rather than honored my race."
Residents say today that the desegregation of schools, positive in some respects, had weakened Eatonville’s cohesion and undermined the confidence of its young people.
“Black kids were used to being hugged – I remember this – they used to hug the teacher in the morning and at night,” said N.Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins’ daughter and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit organization.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students did not come from the same place.
“I wasn’t hugging your teacher because I was white – there’s a cultural gap there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors and artists who passed over prejudices, just like she did, with buoyant, confident and lines like: “How can anyone deny himself the pleasure of my company!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker went to Mrs. Hurston’s anonymous grave and began to struggle to resurrect her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Mrs. Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared in bookstores, reintroducing her into American canons.
The road project came just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter was back in the spotlight.
And this time, Mrs. Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
In 1988, the community began planning a fair for Mrs. Hurston to show what the county could ruin with that road.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the celebration.
After several years, the county has abandoned its road proposal.
“The resurrected idea of the five-way road would have been to put on what you would call bending speed, a real civic pride,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd said it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road project has helped to change the image of the same city.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, started showing up in large numbers, and residents started revisiting the past.
Eatonville entered the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new library (named Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a resurfaced and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still an anomaly in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, you can sometimes feel like a street from the past in a summer rain, in a city as small as the one that was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(90 percent of people are black today.)
Outsiders who come in search of the Eatonville story, of its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permit in advance is necessary to do most of the interviews, and some things – such as the murals in Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and showing black men working in the field – cannot be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Mrs. Jones, a brave and convinced teacher who has a weakness for bright red, still fear that her island community might be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston festival has expanded, a higher level of home pride has also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville the way Mrs. Hurston saw her entire race: beauty, and all problems, not better, not worse, and equally the other racial and ethnic groups in America, proud, creative, hardworking, silly, and mixed.
