Talking asleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to these who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who speak while asleep.
The first time it happens you may be scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It’s a benign sleep disturbance called somnilochiae.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of you have been told that you spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (sleep peeing) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
It is an understudied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also highly variable.
It could be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be convenient to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is an issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives way in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a picture of stress).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to get the child too excited before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a calmer sleep.
Once the somniloquias appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes, it is advisable to consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation of asking him for an interrogation to extract information from him.
You will achieve nothing, because when he is asleep he is not conscious enough to organize his thought.
Besides, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even kidding.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, do not worry, it is not a bad thing, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
