The Interview - Blood Is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it reconquered the public’s confidence that had seriously been wavered by the tainted blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood stocks administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, presided over by Judge Horacio Krever, aimed at clarifying the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and making recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer recur.
While Judge Krever was late in filing their relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
Following reports from Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Society of Blood to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work over the years that followed, we have regained the public’s trust,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had henceforth confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr Décary recalls however that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, we were witnessing the birth in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Décary says.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we establish exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus and not antibodies against the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used until now were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed shortening the period between when the person has been infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk that certain donors will be unknowingly infected and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion today to regain your health without worry,” says the head of the Héma-Québec leadership.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary says before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for an adequate supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which groups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All persons in good health, who are 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria, may nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But the members of this donor network need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and incite them to be a regular donor.
Since current life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and it is expected to draw more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
“Many moms are disappointed that they can’t enjoy this,” since Héma-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all of Quebec’s hospitals.
