Overlap psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose out in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this “game” through experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction and meanwhile the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment were examined by means of the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-prize” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the real value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they win, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be inferred from any previously existing economic theory.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's faculty of economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: food-borne hepatitis A and E (e.g. with water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, there are no vaccines against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifesting through poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and in the whites of the eyes jaundice, the stool becomes light, dark-colored urine and healing can last as long as two - three weeks.
One million people worldwide die annually from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and many times the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore it is very important the premature examination, the systematic medical monitoring.
It is much more frequent in three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shock, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of investigations in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis occurred as follows; they attached a sparkling instrument to the patient’s left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked experiment participants to fix their gaze on two paintings; Sassoferrato’s 17th-century Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci’s 15th-century Lady of the Ermine.
The researchers had hoped that the Virgin Mary spectacle would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt “safe” as “protected” people, “they were reassured and peace reigned in their hearts.”
When they looked at the religious picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can get a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, such as for a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the outcome of the inquiry.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality,” Wright said.
After these formidable results there remains only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if Leonardo’s Madonna or another painter of his stature were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can say: it can be found both in people’s pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what they are interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this still isn’t enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who parallel the Orwellian view do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to be able to fulfill the original objectives of the founders of Google: “Let’s gather all the information in the world into one system!”
According to the leader of Google, the company even after ten years of work that stirred the World is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to treat all the information.
When asked what will happen five years from now, Schmidt said, “I want Google to be able to answer questions like ‘What to do tomorrow?’ or ‘What would be the best job for me?’ – but software won’t be able to answer seemingly simple questions as long as there isn’t enough user information.”
Not all Internet users are aware that during their navigation on the Internet, the searched keywords, IP addresses and pages to which they went when they finished the search are accurately stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can re-check what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches -on this same logic will be based Recommendations, on which the system will offer products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who worry about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear for punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a fact already confirmed that they not only retain, but in justifiable cases also cede to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example in recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over to the Brazilian government the information on its website, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
Instead, netizens who care about people’s rights in May were relieved when the company along with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully demonstrated to the court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google cannot be forced, by any of the points of the constitution, to supply any type of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to get under the pretext of strengthening the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without getting the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
So the opinion about Google is quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who fear providing their personal data because they think that their privacy is damaged, their private life when they start using Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the North American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, Internet users and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the “avant-garde corporation”, not so their rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World, however much both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for its applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between people’s rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the communication channels available, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then they can include them in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, they can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored in the Flickr or in the Picasa automatically appear.
We can know numerous cases from which it follows that for example the bride, seeing the flow of photographs of the next morning of common friends, finds out who her fraudulent boyfriend spent the previous night with or they can dismiss the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the direction of the company: one thing is sure, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person's "on-line" life is what he shows of himself - this is the definition behind the behavior of today's youth.
And the one who wants to hide something, or at least wants to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do it (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses Google’s search system, but leaves no traces).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from being found, but you can replace Google's "online" applications, from word-writing software to image and news-reading applications with alternative versions which do not connect with gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect possible profile about us.
Public opinion almost expects it openly the day that Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of $156 billion is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenue of ad agencies, while services that are being introduced more and more quickly cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software development companies.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example the top management flatly rejected the employees’ protest after doubling the price of the company’s nursery, deemed the unlimited number of employees’ feeding too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to pressure from the Chinese government and the company under the agreement leaked any information that violated the good morals and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the internal regulations of the company says that they will not announce any new service in advance, but only when it is ready to work, what is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years may stir the World: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines of Google will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the Supreme Court of the United States, others fear our own health system, because in it we can create our own problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for the writers of works of science fiction, the Scroogled, novel of the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwellian form that future, in which a man only from the data of Google can be described alarmingly well.
