The smart car mimics the bumblebee's flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not mimicking the obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example, the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at Japan’s CEATEC, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-mimicking BR23C robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, CTO of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of compound eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning as necessary the wheels.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
“If it wasn’t, the robot in the vehicle wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to dodge obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Lab and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the inner most vulnerable layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotary movement and acceleration in addition to braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life span than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, much less the storage.
This device in every second only has to process some input signals and react according to the case.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory is needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, will be able to be incorporated into mass-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the existing obstacles in his path.
This dear child already has a name.
The law’s written version of the $700 billion bailout package has been prepared to be implemented in several phases in order to buy bad loans from banks.
Half of the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to East Coast time during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement around the $700 billion bailout package in total, after several days of discussion - Reuters reported.
We have made significant progress - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic president of the US Congress, stating that it is only necessary to formalize the agreement in a document.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Finance Minister, speaking about the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and be efficient but more measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the car of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, that is, on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (that is, before 2 a.m. on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock markets.
On the so-called emergency bill for economic stabilization of 2008, the U.S. Congress will first vote on Monday and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy shoddy credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Finance Ministry will buy credit-fund securities, badly rated and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special agency, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion can be spent after a new congressional decision.
According to the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it will be able to simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities of credit fund, in addition to other credits of "poisonous" type as well.
The purchase can be made in auctions or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson: The law ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the purchase of bad financial means, its insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - it added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks who are in trouble and waiting for the help of the State will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the American slang calls simply a golden parachute.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of help from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed boss retires.
By buying the bad loans directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the bosses’ compensations are not overstated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations relate only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program as well.
This is the first case in U.S. history that a legal cap on CEO revenues will be in place, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since ultimately they can even obtain profits with the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
Under the bill over the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to repay taxpayers for financial sector losses.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed reservations about the project.
This is not what the American people entrusted us with, that is, they are not protecting taxpayer dollars,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Her fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, said the measures were urged by those responsible for the Wall Street crash.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In the month of August 2008 domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices were up 1.1 percent from July 2008 and down 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose by only a minimal measure, by 0.1 percent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, with 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to the 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices for the chemical production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry sectors there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in the month of August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period – in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors – the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector there was an increase of 13.2 percent, while in the food, beverages and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the global processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water supply topped 18.7 percent the previous year’s prices.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7%) was registered in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in the energy sector and in the intermediary sectors there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the branches that produce consumer goods, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods, 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated at HUF increased 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in a month was reduced by 1.7 percent against the euro and 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
