Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also president of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, deputy of the European People’s Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that afflict Roma children and is also the greatest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organizations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma are left out of the labor market in the first place because of their low level of schooling.
“Most young Roma have not finished secondary school and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can obtain a university diploma.”
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of EU Member States.
According to the MEP, there is a need to raise awareness of these issues widely among both Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the earlier a gypsy student starts school, the more chances they will have to become an active member of the labor market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - said Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to immediately accelerate the processes of school desegregation, for that it is of fundamental importance the correct compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens" - demanded Járóka.
The objective of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organised annually since last year’s Berlin meeting under the banner of the “European Year of Equal Opportunities”, is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European level and at Member State level.
