Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic halls
Historic movie theaters close favoring the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer with effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the big meticons in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono theaters in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new Paradiso cinema, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that perhaps lost forever.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay most are all the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the multiplex is responsible for its disappearance, these three Italian regions are the ones that have registered the largest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interestingly, Bologna, the first Italian city concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect single-room cinema in the historic center than on the outskirts.
Among the planned rules there are mediations of tax facilitation in favor of the managers and advantages for the public in mobility finishes: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
"It's an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore"and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting other measures in place.
It is true that to contrast the extra power of meticons, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a subject that was always important to me: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Paradiso cinema", which I already thought of for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn the other way.
