When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones come down to the stage.
It is an exterminated field that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the great ones like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s along with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was pushed aside, but now that environmental cases and the new rise of oil give momentum to the sector.
London’s World Energy Council (WEC) has estimated by 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity need could be covered by implants that exploit the motion of sea waves.
This amount would be double that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying the technology on ocean energy - the spokesman of a company associated with ha to the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal - and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission to conduct a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It’s a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the U.S. continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to drill further.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
technology to develop.
Experts talk about a technology still at the beginning, because marine energy has a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts such as those in Portugal or Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a higher environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which causes the boas to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore via submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type under development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines on New York’s East River.
The movement of the water when there are tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electric Power, right now merits the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is mostly about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others approaching the coast, have invested $7 and a half million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
